"Muller S.","The post-glacial history of Pulsatilla vernalis and Daphne cneorum in Bitcherland, inferred from the phytosociological study of their current habitat",1997,"Global Ecology and Biogeography Letters","6","2",,"129","137",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031474054&partnerID=40&md5=55032d3c7705af5529a37a52ade0333a","Laboratoire de Phytoécologie, Centre de Recherches Ecologiques, Université de Metz, Ile du Saulcy, F57045-Metz, France","Muller, S., Laboratoire de Phytoécologie, Centre de Recherches Ecologiques, Université de Metz, Ile du Saulcy, F57045-Metz, France","The post-glacial history of Pulsatilla vernalis and Daphne cneorum in Bitcherland is reconstructed by using a phytosociological study of their current habitat. These two species form part of the mesohydric heathland association Daphno cneori-Callunetum. This plant community is characterized by the co-existence of a group of sub-atlantic species and a group with continental affinities in which the two species are found. The presence of this same continental floristic assemblage in the sandy pinewoods of Peucedano-Pinetum of central and oriental Europe leads to the conclusion that D. cneorum and P. vernalis constitute relict species from the Boreal Period in the Bitche region. During this period, the climatic climax of the area should have consisted of pine forests having approximately similar vegetation to the current east-european Peucedano-Pinetum association. The global warming which followed this period caused the replacement of this association of pine forests by an oak association, Luzulo-Quercetum, repressing the semiheliophilic species, among them P. vernalis and D. cneorum, to the clearings and edges of these oak forests. These two species were then able to colonize the secondary heaths, created by the over-exploitation of forests since the Middle Ages. The development of intensive forestry practices in the XIX century has caused the regression of these two species, which nowadays are found only in the military grounds in Bitche.","Boreal Period; Continental; Daphne cneorum; Heath; Oak forest; Phytogeography; Phytosociology; Pine forest; Pulsatilla vernalis; Vosges Mountains","heathland; Holocene; oak forest; pine forest; France, Bitcherland, Alsace; Daphne cneorum; Daphno cneori-Callunetum; Luzulo-Quercetum; Peucedano-Pinetum; Pulsatilla vernalis; Ranunculaceae; Thymelaeaceae",,,,,,"Aymonin, G., Quelques aspects des phytocoenoses à Daphne cneorum, en particulier en Pays Basque français (1958) Bull. Centre Et. Rech. Sci. Biarritz, 2, pp. 51-91; Aymonin, G., Essai d'une monographie écologique du Daphne cneorum (1959) Rev. Gén. Bot., 66, pp. 281-328; Bernard, A., Carbiener, R., Etude des écotypes d'espèces collectives praticoles inféodées aux prairies subalpines primaires (Calamagrostion arundinaceae) des Hautes Vosges. Comparaisons aux taxons collinéens et planitiaires correspondant de la région Alsace. 2ème partie: Les taxons à affinités continentales (1981) Doc. Phyt. NS, 5, pp. 375-408; Carbiener, R., Un remarquable groupement végétal des hautes Vosges: La Calamagrostidaie subalpine (1963) C. R. Acad. Sc. Paris, 256, pp. 4967-4969; Carbiener, R., Subalpine Hochgrasprärien im herzynischen Gebirgsraum Europas, mit besonderer Berücksichtigung der Vogesen und des Massif Central (1969) Mitt. Flor. -Soz. Arbeitsgem., 14, pp. 322-345. , N.F; Conard, H.S., Phylogeny and ontogeny in plant sociology (1954) Vegetatio, 5-6, pp. 11-16; Edelman, H.J., (1985) Late Glacial and Holocene Vegetation Development of ""la Goutte Loiselot"" (Vosges, France), , Dissertation, University of Utrecht; Glazek, T., Preliminary investigations on the ecology of Daphne cneorum (1969) Rocz. Dendr., 23, pp. 63-84. , in Polish, with English summary; Guinochet, M., (1973) Phytosociologie, 227p. , Masson, Paris; Hatt, J.P., Contribution à l'analyse pollinique des tourbières du Nord-Est de la France (1937) Bull. Service Carte Géol. Als. Lorr., 4, pp. 1-79; Hohene